    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-11-29T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-11-29T21:00:00-05:00" n="414"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13295: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-30T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 30, 1935—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>118. Note dated November 29 has been received from the Foreign Office reading in
                    translation as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I have the honor to recall that because of his attempted revolt against
                            the nation the National Government has issued an explicit <pb
                                facs="0568" n="456" xml:id="pg_456"/> order that Yin Yu-keng,
                            administrative superintendent of the Luanchow-Shanhaikwan area of Hopei
                            Province, be dismissed from his post and arrested for punishment. All of
                            his activities while he was administrative superintendent of the
                            Luanchow-Shanhaikwan and Chunhsien-Chunyun areas which have not been
                            approved by the former Political Affairs Adjustment Commission of the
                            Executive Yuan at Peiping, the former Peiping branch of the National
                            Army Military Affairs Commission and the Hopei Provincial Government,
                            and all of his activities after his rebellion should be considered as of
                            no effect.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
